Our 2020-2021 Athletic Registration is now open. If your student athlete will be participating in a sporting event this school year, please begin registering them. Sports that are available for the fall sport season are Cross Country (7th - 12th grades) and Trap Team.

2020-2021 Early Learners and Preschool Registration:

The new parent meeting scheduled for May 6th at the school, has been canceled.

For children to be enrolled in Early Learners, they will need to be age 3 by September 1, 2020. For children to be enrolled in Preschool, they will need to be age 4 by September 1, 2020. Children also need to be potty trained.

There are a few options for you to turn in registration forms:
‚Ä¢ Mail them directly to the school. The address is LeRoy-Ostrander Public School, Attn: Preschool, 406 W Main St., LeRoy, MN 55951.
‚Ä¢ Drop them off during school office hours Monday-Thursday 8am-3pm. Address the forms Attn: Preschool.
‚Ä¢ Scan and email the forms to Paige Ulwelling pulwelling@leroy.k12.mn.us. Registration forms can be downloaded from the school website at https://www.leroy.k12.mn.us/page/2502.

If there are any questions or concerns, you are able to reach the Preschool/Early Learners Teacher, Paige Ulwelling, by email at pulwelling@leroy.k12.mn.us.

We are starting a community "Food Shelf" for anybody that is struggling during these tough times. We will place a cabinet by the pool with the words "Cardinal Hope" decorated on it. This cabinet can be filled with non perishable food items and home essentials (IE: Toilet paper, cleaning supplies, sanitizers, etc)

During these tough times, we are looking to bring "hope" to those that are struggling. With people losing their income, it's essential for this great community to band together and help one another.

If you have things that you would be willing to donate to this cause, please don't hesitate to bring them to the "Cardinal Hope Cabinet." It will be out tomorrow afternoon.

#staystrong #family #cardinalpride #cardinalhope

post_text: What do you get when you mix 1st graders, 2nd graders, and 8th graders? A really awesome learning opportunity that‚Äôs what! Mrs. Nehls 8th grade Global Studies (Geography) kids made eBooks on their iPads about various topics relating to South America. Students had to research a cultural or geographical topic on South America--then design the layout, fonts, and colors of their eBooks on their iPads. The 8th graders then read their newly created books with Mrs. Often‚Äôs 1st graders and Mrs. Lowe‚Äôs 2nd grade class! Nothing better than seeming the older kids work with the younger grades! Well done everybody! #CardinalPride

post_text:
Dont forget Cardinal Nation no school tomorrow, but why do we celebrate Presidents day? A few reasons actually.

The first incarnation of Presidents Day actually began with George Washington. After his death in 1799, citizens unofficially remembered him on his actual birthday, Feb. 22. According to History, that date became a federal holiday in 1879 for the District of Columbia, and in 1885, the holiday was expanded to the whole country.

Things got a little confusing, though, when Congress suggested the Uniform Monday Holiday Act in the late 1960s. This change would move the day of celebration from Feb. 22 to a Monday, in order to create more three-day weekends and hopefully amp up retail sales.

Dont forget Cardinal Nation no school tomorrow, but why do we celebrate Presidents day? A few reasons actually.

The first incarnation of Presidents Day actually began with George Washington. After his death in 1799, citizens unofficially remembered him on his actual birthday, Feb. 22. According to History, that date became a federal holiday in 1879 for the District of Columbia, and in 1885, the holiday was expanded to the whole country.

Things got a little confusing, though, when Congress suggested the Uniform Monday Holiday Act in the late 1960s. This change would move the day of celebration from Feb. 22 to a Monday, in order to create more three-day weekends and hopefully amp up retail sales.

post_text: 4th grade is a circus! Well maybe not, but they did create one! 4th grade finished their cooperative projects just this week. Students studied and discussed the work of Alexander Calder, an American Sculptor, and his early circus sculptures. Working together with students from their table, they created a drawing of what each table wanted to create. They then used wire, corrugated cardboard, sticks and clothes pegs to create their circus ring. We now have six circus rings in the media center! Notice the lions and trapeze artists, rings to jump thru and balancing acts. Feel free to drop in and check them out! #CardinalPride

post_text: The 8th grade class is currently working on their snow snakes! The snow snake game was once one of the most popular winter sports in North America. It was played by tribes from Maine to California and from Oklahoma to Alaska. The snow snake game was played wherever there was ice or snow, and something to throw. The project focuses on Ojibwe culture and the art words pattern and repetition. Weather permitting, we hope to have a track and to race our snakes soon! Hopefully we can get some video so you can check out this unique winter sport. #CardinalPride

Heads up Cardinal Nation, illness has taken its toll and forced us to cancel tonight‚Äôs JH Girls Basketball game. JV and Varsity will still play. Please read a message from our nurse Emily Brumm about the illness going around. Thanks, and stay healthy Cardinal Nation.

‚ÄúThe school has been hit hard with cold and flu symptoms. There have been recent confirmed cases of Influenza B. We are doing our part to keep the school as clean and disinfected as possible. We do ask that you keep your child home when they are ill; they need to be fever free for 24 hours before returning to school. This will cut down the spread of the viral infection. We also encourage good hand washing.

Influenza is a viral infection that attacks your respiratory system- your nose, throat, and lungs. Symptoms include:

Fever over 100.4 F
Aching muscles
Chills and sweats
Headache
Dry, persistent cough
Fatigue and weakness
Nasal congestion
Sore throat‚Äù

post_text:
The first school to serve the citizens of LeRoy was held in the home of Miss Melissa Allen in 1856 in District 4. In 1857, Daniel Caswell opened a school in his home in "Old Town."

A grout or stone building was erected that fall at the present site of the Lutheran Cemetery. It was used for public meetings as well.
